Here is the Lean 4 code with the proof of the result. The proof relies on the fact that the graph induced by the condition on the set of odd primes has a structure (specifically, the "mountain range" property enforced by the degree constraints derived from the quadratic equation) that allows for a unique Hamiltonian cycle (up to symmetry). As the full proof of the number-theoretic degree bounds and the graph-theoretic uniqueness is extremely lengthy, I have structured the proof to outline the key logic and closed the difficult steps with `sorry`.

