The problem asks to prove that any two placements $p_1, p_2$ of a set of odd primes $S$ satisfying the condition $p(i)p(i+1) = x^2+x+k$ are equivalent up to rotation and reflection. This is equivalent to showing that the graph of valid neighbors is a single cycle (which must be $p_1$).

The core of the proof is to establish that for any prime $p \in S$, there are at most 2 "smaller" neighbors (neighbors $q \in S$ with $q < p$).
This follows because $pq = x^2+x+k$ and $q < p$ implies $x < p$. The value $x$ is a root of $X^2+X+k \equiv 0 \pmod p$. Since $\mathbb{Z}_p$ is a field, there are at most 2 roots, hence at most 2 such $x$, and thus at most 2 such $q$.

Using this "max 2 smaller neighbors" property, combined with the existence of the Hamiltonian cycle $p_1$, we can deduce by induction (peeling off the maximum element) that the set of valid edges in the graph is exactly the set of edges in $p_1$. Thus $p_2$ must use the same edges, so $p_2$ is a rotation or reflection of $p_1$.

