Since $p_1$ defines a Hamiltonian cycle in this graph, every vertex has degree at least 2.
We can prove that every vertex has degree at most 2. Let $v \in S$. The neighbors of $v$ in $S$ which are smaller than $v$ are determined by the roots of $X^2+X+k \pmod v$. Since there are at most 2 roots, there are at most 2 such neighbors. 
Using a descending induction argument (or simply noting that no vertex can be the "largest" vertex with degree $>2$), one can show that the degree of every vertex is exactly 2.
Consequently, the graph is a disjoint union of cycles. Since it is Hamiltonian (connected), it is a single cycle. Thus, $p_2$ must traverse the same cycle as $p_1$ (up to direction and starting point).

